            <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">All surgery carries risk.</h3>
            <p class="text-gray-700 text-sm">
              <strong>Major complication rate for MGB: 2-4%</strong> (lower than traditional bypass: 3-5%). Most Melbourne patients experience no serious complications, but it's critical to understand potential risks before proceeding.
            </p>
          </div>

          <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
            <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-xl p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Serious Complications (Rare)</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-gray-700">
                <li>
                  <strong class="text-red-600">Anastomotic Leak (1-2%):</strong> Connection breaks down, leaking stomach contents into abdomen. Requires emergency surgery. Symptoms: severe pain, fever, rapid heart rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong class="text-red-600">Bleeding (1-2%):</strong> Internal bleeding requiring transfusion or reoperation. Symptoms: low blood pressure, black stools, weakness.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong class="text-red-600">Bowel Obstruction (1-3%):</strong> Intestine becomes blocked (scar tissue, internal hernia). Requires surgery to fix. Symptoms: severe abdominal pain, vomiting, inability to pass gas.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong class="text-red-600">Blood Clots (0.5-1%):</strong> DVT (deep vein thrombosis) or pulmonary embolism. Prevented with blood thinners and early mobilization. Symptoms: leg swelling, chest pain, shortness of breath.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong class="text-red-600">Death (less than 0.3%):</strong> Extremely rare. Risk similar to gallbladder removal. Melbourne surgeons have excellent safety records.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>

            <div class="bg-gray-50 rounded-xl p-6">
              <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Common Side Effects</h3>
              <ul class="space-y-3 text-sm text-gray-700">
                <li>
                  <strong class="text-orange-600">Dumping Syndrome (30-40%):</strong> Eating sugar/fats causes nausea, sweating, diarrhea, rapid heart rate. Acts as negative reinforcement‚Äîhelps you avoid unhealthy foods.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong class="text-orange-600">Bile Reflux (5-10%):</strong> Bile flows back into stomach/esophagus causing heartburn-like pain. Higher with MGB than traditional bypass. Managed with medications; 2-5% require revision surgery.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong class="text-orange-600">Vitamin Deficiencies (if supplements skipped):</strong> B12, iron, calcium, vitamin D deficiencies develop. Causes fatigue, anemia, bone loss. Prevented with daily vitamins and annual blood tests.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong class="text-orange-600">Gallstones (10-15%):</strong> Rapid weight loss increases risk. Some surgeons remove gallbladder during MGB. Symptoms: right upper abdominal pain after fatty meals.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong class="text-orange-600">Excess Skin:</strong> Significant weight loss leaves loose skin (abdomen, arms, thighs). May require plastic surgery 12-18 months post-op.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-xl p-8 border-2 border-blue-200">
            <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Long-Term Risks</h3>
            <div class="space-y-4 text-sm text-gray-700">
              <div>
                <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1">Nutritional Deficiencies (10-30% if non-compliant)</h4>
                <p>Malabsorption means vitamins/minerals aren't absorbed well. <strong>You must take daily supplements for life.</strong> Without them: anemia, osteoporosis, neuropathy, cognitive issues. Annual blood tests catch deficiencies early.</p>
              </div>
              <div>
                <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1">Weight Regain (15-25% of patients)</h4>
                <p>Some weight regain (10-15% of lost weight) after 2-3 years is normal. Caused by stomach pouch stretching, poor diet habits, lack of exercise. Rarely requires revision‚Äîusually managed with dietitian support.</p>
              </div>
              <div>
                <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1">Stricture/Narrowing (3-5%)</h4>
                <p>Anastomosis narrows, making swallowing difficult. Fixed with endoscopic dilation (balloon stretched through scope). Usually occurs within first 3 months.</p>
              </div>
              <div>
                <h4 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-1">Marginal Ulcers (2-5%)</h4>
                <p>Ulcer forms at anastomosis. Caused by NSAIDs (ibuprofen), smoking, or stress. Symptoms: gnawing abdominal pain. Treated with PPIs (proton pump inhibitors). Avoid NSAIDs lifelong.</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

